The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Karat delinks election and deal
                                                                                                               Karat delinks election and deal
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	New Delhi, March 9: CPM general secretary Prakash Karat today said the date for the next meeting of the UPA-Left committee on the nuclear deal was likely to be announced tomorrow.        
	Foreign minister Pranab Mukherjee was holding talks with Left parties on a mutually convenient date, he said after a three-day central committee meeting.        
	He, however, sought to delink the deal from elections. This issue and elections are different issues, Karat said when asked whether the Left would withdraw support if the government proceeded with the agreement.        
	The comments came a day after Mukherjee ruled out the possibility of early polls and termed the threats from the Left a known position.        
	Karat said the Left was in no hurry to know the outcome of the IAEA meeting on India-specific safeguards.        
	We will see what they (government) say in the committee (meeting).... I cannot presume what is there in the text (the draft safeguards agreement) as I am not party to the negotiations, he said.        
	Following reports that the draft agreement had been finalised, Karat had written to Mukherjee to convene a meeting by March 15. On Friday, CPI general secretary A.B. Bardhan had threatened to withdraw support.         
	CPM leader Sitaram Yechury said the government should take the next step on the basis of the panels findings. If the committee says it (deal) is not correct, the government has to follow it.                                                                                                                                                                           
